WEBVTT

00:03.128 --> 00:04.546
GROOTENDORST: Don't move.

00:04.546 --> 00:06.131
SILBERBAUER: We know that you
are hiding Jews here.

00:06.131 --> 00:08.133
MIEP: Max.
MAX: I need your help.

00:10.052 --> 00:12.054
OFFICER BAARS: Nobody moves.

00:12.054 --> 00:13.680
JAN: See you after the war.

00:13.680 --> 00:17.184
The Nazis are taking more
and more people every day.

00:17.184 --> 00:19.478
EDITH: I have this
bad feeling, Miep.

00:19.478 --> 00:21.688
I can't shake it.

00:21.688 --> 00:22.689
SILBERBAUER: Open it.

00:22.689 --> 00:24.816
(whistling)

00:24.816 --> 00:27.027
OTTO: Wait, wait.
Please. No.

00:27.027 --> 00:28.320
SILBERBAUER: Is it just
the two of you in here?

00:28.320 --> 00:29.196
OTTO: Wait.

00:31.907 --> 00:33.200
SILBERBAUER: Why
are you doing this?

00:33.200 --> 00:34.243
What the hell am I
supposed to do with you now?

00:34.243 --> 00:35.953
MIEP: Please, just
leave the girls.

00:35.953 --> 00:36.995
SILBERBAUER: You can stay.

00:36.995 --> 00:37.996
I'm doing this as
a favor to you.

00:37.996 --> 00:39.331
MIEP: I worked out what to do.

00:39.331 --> 00:41.375
We bribe him, we
buy the Franks back.

00:41.375 --> 00:43.043
JAN: We're gonna
need a lot of money.

00:43.043 --> 00:45.921
MIEP: If I don't try
everything I possibly can,

00:45.921 --> 00:49.132
I don't think I'll be
able to live with myself.

01:01.311 --> 01:08.193
♪ ♪

01:15.367 --> 01:22.165
♪ ♪

01:26.211 --> 01:27.754
MIEP: Hello.

01:27.754 --> 01:29.506
I'm looking for
a Nazi officer.

01:29.506 --> 01:30.507
KRIMINALASSISTENT: Name?

01:30.507 --> 01:32.592
MIEP: Oh, mine or, or his?

01:32.592 --> 01:34.428
I, I don't know his name.

01:34.428 --> 01:36.263
He's, he's tall,
reddish blond hair.

01:36.263 --> 01:37.806
KRIMINALASSISTENT: And what
would you like me to do,

01:37.806 --> 01:40.017
go around and check hair color?

01:40.017 --> 01:41.685
MIEP: He was in charge of an
arrest two days ago at

01:41.685 --> 01:43.312
263 Prinsengracht.

01:43.312 --> 01:44.938
It's urgent that
I speak to him.

02:08.295 --> 02:13.967
♪ ♪

02:19.306 --> 02:21.308
SILBERBAUER: What are
you doing here?

02:21.308 --> 02:23.935
MIEP: I know my friends
are being held here.

02:24.686 --> 02:28.774
This bag contains
a lot of money.

02:29.733 --> 02:32.652
Let them go and it's yours.

02:39.951 --> 02:43.080
First, my friends.

02:43.080 --> 02:44.664
SILBERBAUER: I could
have you arrested.

02:44.664 --> 02:45.832
MIEP: Then you'd have to
explain why you didn't

02:45.832 --> 02:47.209
arrest me the other day.

02:47.209 --> 02:48.335
SILBERBAUER: How dare you coming
in talk to me like this.

02:48.335 --> 02:50.962
MIEP: How would
you explain it?

02:50.962 --> 02:53.382
She's from Vienna, so am I.

02:53.382 --> 02:55.258
So, I saw her as a person.

02:55.258 --> 02:56.968
I took pity.

02:56.968 --> 03:00.222
SILBERBAUER: Get out.
MIEP: Take pity on my friends.

03:00.222 --> 03:02.391
I realize it's a
big risk for you.

03:02.391 --> 03:04.017
I do.

03:04.017 --> 03:06.144
But they are people, too.

03:06.144 --> 03:09.147
They're fathers, and mothers,

03:09.147 --> 03:12.442
and children, children.

03:14.319 --> 03:16.822
The Allies are
nearly at the gate,

03:16.822 --> 03:20.325
and it will be you being
arrested one day soon.

03:20.325 --> 03:23.829
Wouldn't you like to have me
vouch for you at your trial?

03:23.829 --> 03:27.416
In the end, he did
the right thing.

03:27.416 --> 03:29.918
He saved the lives
of eight people.

03:59.030 --> 04:00.449
SILBERBAUER: You have to go.

04:00.449 --> 04:01.992
MIEP: My friends.

04:03.368 --> 04:04.744
SILBERBAUER: No.

04:04.744 --> 04:06.246
MIEP: I'm begging you.

04:06.246 --> 04:07.205
SILBERBAUER: I did not arrest
you the other day because

04:07.205 --> 04:09.332
you are nothing.

04:10.333 --> 04:12.377
You are nobody.

04:12.377 --> 04:14.588
Now go.

04:25.849 --> 04:29.227
MIEP: Sir, sir, sir.
Excuse me, sir.

04:29.227 --> 04:32.272
I overheard you saying that
the cells are crowded and

04:32.272 --> 04:34.399
I, I think I can help.

04:34.399 --> 04:36.568
Your subordinate recently
brought in a group of people

04:36.568 --> 04:40.739
who I'd, I'd happily
pay to be released.

04:41.156 --> 04:42.491
I'll tell no one.

04:42.491 --> 04:44.409
You'll be protected.

04:44.409 --> 04:45.869
KURT: I'm sorry.

04:45.869 --> 04:47.287
Who did you say you were?

04:47.287 --> 04:49.873
MIEP: I'm a friend of, of 10
very good people who are

04:49.873 --> 04:52.501
being held downstairs.

04:52.501 --> 04:55.420
KURT: Jews?
MIEP: Uh, most of them, yes.

04:55.420 --> 04:58.131
KURT: Well, then they're really
not good people, are they?

04:58.965 --> 05:01.843
MIEP: This bag, this bag
contains a lot of money.

05:01.843 --> 05:02.886
It's yours if...

05:02.886 --> 05:04.804
KURT: You're bribing me?

05:04.804 --> 05:06.723
You're bribing an
officer to release Jews?

05:06.723 --> 05:08.391
MIEP: One of them was an
officer himself in the

05:08.391 --> 05:10.977
Great War, Otto Frank.

05:10.977 --> 05:13.939
He was decorated, a lieutenant.
Look him up.

05:16.066 --> 05:18.485
KURT: Let me see that money.

05:26.701 --> 05:28.787
You!

05:28.787 --> 05:30.664
Remove this woman from
the building please.

05:30.664 --> 05:32.916
MIEP: What? What?

05:32.916 --> 05:34.876
Where is your conscience?

05:34.876 --> 05:37.212
Where are your morals?

05:38.713 --> 05:40.966
Let me go!

05:43.677 --> 05:44.844
JAN: Miep.

05:44.844 --> 05:46.012
Miep, come on.

05:46.012 --> 05:47.347
MIEP: You weren't...
JAN: It's okay.

05:47.347 --> 05:49.015
MIEP: You weren't
supposed to, to come.

05:49.015 --> 05:50.809
JAN: I was going out
of my mind at home.

05:50.809 --> 05:52.811
I was afraid they're
gonna arrest you, too.

05:52.811 --> 05:54.354
I was about to go
in looking for you.

05:54.354 --> 05:56.231
MIEP: They took,
they took the money.

05:56.231 --> 05:58.108
Now they have our
friends and our money.

05:58.108 --> 05:59.901
JAN: Hey, don't, don't cry.

05:59.901 --> 06:01.069
MIEP: And they're in there...
JAN: Miep.

06:01.069 --> 06:02.237
MIEP: They're in there.

06:02.237 --> 06:03.363
JAN: Don't let them
see you cry, please.

06:03.363 --> 06:05.657
Don't let them see you cry. Okay.

06:05.657 --> 06:07.242
MAN: Hurry up. You have
three more pick-ups today.

06:07.242 --> 06:08.785
JAN: Let's go home.
MIEP: Wait.

06:08.785 --> 06:11.872
It's, it's Puls. Okay.

06:12.163 --> 06:13.331
We have to go, we have
to go and get everything

06:13.331 --> 06:14.416
before they take it.

06:14.416 --> 06:16.501
JAN: Okay. Come on.

06:18.295 --> 06:20.297
MIEP: Oh, Bep!

06:20.297 --> 06:22.215
BEP: I wasn't sure
whether to come in.

06:22.215 --> 06:23.925
MIEP: Do you have
keys for the annex?

06:23.925 --> 06:26.177
I know the Nazis took them,
but I made another set.

06:26.177 --> 06:27.888
BEP: Uh, Mr. Kleiman had them.

06:27.888 --> 06:28.972
But the Nazis
said not to go up.

06:28.972 --> 06:30.223
MIEP: Let's look
in Kleiman's desk.

06:30.223 --> 06:32.434
JAN: Yes.

06:34.853 --> 06:37.022
MIEP: Wait.
He hid them in a, in a file.

06:37.022 --> 06:39.441
He had a system, remember?
We made fun of him.

06:39.441 --> 06:41.234
BEP: Oh, yes. Um...

06:41.234 --> 06:47.115
Key, key to his heart,
apple pie, pie chart.

06:47.115 --> 06:48.366
Florence Nightingale!

06:48.366 --> 06:50.327
MIEP: Florence Nightingale!

06:50.327 --> 06:51.786
JAN: How'd you get at
Florence Nightingale?

06:51.786 --> 06:53.997
MIEP: Florence Nightingale,
she invented the pie chart

06:53.997 --> 06:55.332
or something.

06:55.332 --> 06:57.709
I don't know.
He's weird.

06:58.710 --> 07:01.171
Got them.

07:01.171 --> 07:03.632
BEP: But the Nazis said...
JAN: Hey, come on.

07:10.972 --> 07:12.474
BEP: We shouldn't be here.

07:12.474 --> 07:14.059
MIEP: We have to find any
valuables and hide them before

07:14.059 --> 07:15.393
Puls gets here.

07:15.393 --> 07:17.646
JAN: We can do this fast
if we'll work together.

07:24.736 --> 07:25.904
MIEP: I'll check upstairs.

07:25.904 --> 07:28.323
You two check the bedrooms.

07:39.417 --> 07:46.132
♪ ♪

08:00.772 --> 08:07.529
♪ ♪

08:31.594 --> 08:36.057
ANNE: Miep?
I'm writing about everyone.

08:49.028 --> 08:52.032
MIEP: They emptied
Mr. Frank's briefcase.

08:52.032 --> 08:56.119
JAN: To steal all the valuables,
really not much left.

08:56.745 --> 08:59.748
BEP: They've taken all
the silver and the money.

09:14.637 --> 09:17.724
MIEP: Wait, wait.

09:17.724 --> 09:20.518
This, this is Anne's diary.

09:21.853 --> 09:23.146
She kept it in his briefcase.

09:23.146 --> 09:25.607
Collect up the papers quickly.

09:34.783 --> 09:41.623
♪ ♪

09:44.292 --> 09:45.877
Bep, don't read that.

09:45.877 --> 09:47.796
BEP: But I see my name.
She wrote something about me.

09:47.796 --> 09:50.799
MIEP: Yeah. Probably
about how nosy you are.

09:51.841 --> 09:54.886
It's Anne's.
It's private.

09:59.682 --> 10:02.685
JAN: Right, all locked up.

10:06.523 --> 10:09.651
BEP: Now what do we do?

10:16.282 --> 10:23.706
♪ ♪

10:23.706 --> 10:26.042
MIEP: Thanks, Bep.

10:26.918 --> 10:29.587
Katrien, these files are the
only clients we have left.

10:29.587 --> 10:31.464
I need you to start
generating new business.

10:31.464 --> 10:33.424
KATRIEN: How can
I sell pectin?

10:33.424 --> 10:35.760
The Germans have cut off all
food supplies to Amsterdam.

10:35.760 --> 10:37.470
There's no fruit to make jam.

10:37.470 --> 10:38.930
MIEP: How does my hair look?

10:38.930 --> 10:40.306
KATRIEN: It, it looks fine.

10:40.306 --> 10:41.516
MIEP: No.
It looks better than fine.

10:41.516 --> 10:43.226
It looks thick and shiny.

10:43.226 --> 10:44.686
You wanna know why?

10:44.686 --> 10:46.855
Because I've been eating pectin,
a teaspoon every morning.

10:46.855 --> 10:48.773
It's helping
with my nails, too.

10:48.773 --> 10:50.358
So, there's no fruit?

10:50.358 --> 10:51.734
Sell pectin as a beauty aid.

10:51.734 --> 10:53.069
Sell it to help
with stomach cramps.

10:53.069 --> 10:54.487
Sell it to help
with heartburn.

10:54.487 --> 10:55.488
KATRIEN: Does it
help heartburn?

10:55.488 --> 10:56.656
MIEP: It might!

10:56.656 --> 10:57.782
The point is, I just
need you to sell it.

10:57.782 --> 10:59.701
We have five
standing clients left.

10:59.701 --> 11:01.536
I need you to go door to door.

11:01.536 --> 11:03.580
KATRIEN: Maybe it's
time to give up, Miep.

11:03.580 --> 11:05.582
Sell the business.

11:05.582 --> 11:07.834
My husband knows a man in
Germany who might buy it.

11:07.834 --> 11:10.461
We could split the
profits among all of us.

11:10.461 --> 11:12.547
Mr. Frank is gone.

11:12.547 --> 11:14.674
Do you really think
he's coming back?

11:20.555 --> 11:22.891
MIEP: It's your severance.
You can go.

11:22.891 --> 11:24.726
KATRIEN: I'm just being honest
because I care about you.

11:24.726 --> 11:25.852
MIEP: No. Can you
please just leave

11:25.852 --> 11:28.354
before I physically remove you?

11:34.903 --> 11:41.075
♪ ♪

11:42.619 --> 11:46.122
JOHANNES: How's it going,
Madam Director?

11:46.122 --> 11:49.292
BEP: He just walked
in like he never left!

11:49.584 --> 11:52.003
JOHANNES: Kugler and I were
sent to a camp in Amersfoort

11:52.003 --> 11:54.839
for political prisoners.

11:56.049 --> 11:58.635
I was released by the
Red Cross a few days ago

11:58.635 --> 12:01.262
because of my health.

12:01.262 --> 12:05.350
I've never been so
happy to have an ulcer.

12:07.435 --> 12:10.146
MIEP: And the others?

12:14.901 --> 12:18.696
JOHANNES: I haven't seen them
since the day of the arrest.

12:19.072 --> 12:21.866
The camp I was in was bad.

12:21.866 --> 12:25.119
I can't imagine the
place they were sent.

12:25.119 --> 12:26.704
I'm worried.

12:26.704 --> 12:29.332
I'm really worried.

12:29.332 --> 12:31.834
MIEP: They're strong.

12:31.834 --> 12:35.213
They are.
They're strong.

12:35.213 --> 12:37.757
JOHANNES: So are you.

12:37.757 --> 12:40.802
You've managed to
keep this place going.

12:40.802 --> 12:44.347
MIEP: Well, we're
teetering on penniless,

12:44.347 --> 12:47.266
and I just fired my
best salesperson.

12:47.266 --> 12:49.268
JOHANNES: Well, the Allies.

12:49.268 --> 12:50.395
MIEP: If you say
they're almost here,

12:50.395 --> 12:52.855
I will actually strangle you.

12:52.855 --> 12:54.816
Sorry, it's just...

12:54.816 --> 12:56.484
I've been hearing
that for months now and

12:56.484 --> 12:58.403
they bypassed Amsterdam
altogether and just pushed

12:58.403 --> 13:00.446
straight to Germany.

13:00.446 --> 13:02.532
The Nazis left here know
that they've lost but they're

13:02.532 --> 13:04.325
angry, so they're
taking it out on us.

13:04.325 --> 13:08.955
And there's no food,
literally none.

13:08.955 --> 13:11.207
And now they're rounding up
all the Dutch men and

13:11.207 --> 13:12.917
sending them to work camps.

13:12.917 --> 13:15.378
So, Jan's staying inside.

13:15.378 --> 13:18.298
Now, it's just the women
left to keep everything going.

13:18.298 --> 13:23.344
JOHANNES: Well, now you've got
an old sick man to help you.

13:24.053 --> 13:26.389
MIEP: Good.

13:29.809 --> 13:32.729
They are strong, Mr. Kleiman.

13:32.729 --> 13:36.149
They'll survive.

13:37.692 --> 13:40.236
Now, we just have to.

13:44.490 --> 13:46.701
JAN: Thank you.

13:48.244 --> 13:51.122
MIEP: You can start.

14:05.094 --> 14:08.139
Do you like it?

14:10.475 --> 14:12.351
JAN: It's not bad.

14:12.351 --> 14:14.604
MIEP: Someone told me
that tulip bulbs have more

14:14.604 --> 14:16.481
nutrients in
them than potatoes.

14:16.481 --> 14:20.068
(coughing)

14:20.068 --> 14:23.362
JAN: Was it a Nazi
who told you that?

14:24.864 --> 14:27.158
MIEP: You don't like it?

14:27.158 --> 14:30.703
JAN: It's tulip
bulb soup, Miep.

14:31.079 --> 14:33.915
I know we have to
eat something, but

14:33.915 --> 14:37.168
we don't have to pretend
we like it, do we?

14:37.919 --> 14:41.255
MIEP: I like it.

14:42.507 --> 14:45.176
Hmm.

14:45.176 --> 14:47.887
JAN: You know what I like?

14:47.887 --> 14:51.891
I like watching you
pretend to like it.

14:51.891 --> 14:54.685
Hmm.

14:56.354 --> 14:59.732
(laughing)

14:59.732 --> 15:02.568
MIEP: Oh, my God,
it tastes like dirt.

15:02.568 --> 15:04.362
JAN: It tastes
like actual dirt.

15:04.362 --> 15:08.074
MIEP: It tastes like
if dirt had gone off.

15:08.616 --> 15:11.202
JAN: We're eating rotten dirt.

15:11.202 --> 15:14.622
(crying)

15:14.622 --> 15:16.874
Why are you crying?

15:16.874 --> 15:18.876
Miep.

15:19.961 --> 15:23.714
MIEP: I tried so
hard to get food today.

15:23.714 --> 15:27.718
And I walked, walked for
hours, farm to farm and then

15:27.718 --> 15:31.097
I needed to burn some of the
newspapers to make this really

15:31.097 --> 15:32.682
horrible soup.

15:32.682 --> 15:37.520
And now we can't make a fire
because there's no firewood.

15:38.229 --> 15:40.231
JAN: Wait there.

15:41.399 --> 15:42.942
MIEP: What are you doing?

15:42.942 --> 15:45.903
(grunting, smashing)

15:45.903 --> 15:47.655
What are you doing?

15:47.655 --> 15:48.865
JAN: Making firewood.

15:48.865 --> 15:51.033
MIEP: That's Mrs.
Stoppelman's chair.

15:51.033 --> 15:53.494
JAN: And now it's all fire.

15:53.494 --> 15:55.788
MIEP: Jan!
JAN: No. No.

15:55.788 --> 15:58.124
I'm not sitting here
watching my wife freeze.

15:58.124 --> 15:59.792
It's bad enough I have to hide
in the house while you are out

15:59.792 --> 16:01.335
getting my food for me.

16:01.335 --> 16:02.712
No. I'm doing this.

16:02.712 --> 16:04.172
I need to do something.

16:04.172 --> 16:06.549
I'm doing this.

16:08.050 --> 16:14.849
(plane flying overhead)

16:17.894 --> 16:20.021
MIEP: I was just, I'm not
even gonna bother going

16:20.021 --> 16:21.272
under the table.

16:21.272 --> 16:23.274
I almost want a German
bomb to take me out.

16:23.274 --> 16:24.901
JAN: Oh, my God.

16:24.901 --> 16:27.278
MIEP: Jan, I'm joking.
I'm joking.

16:27.278 --> 16:28.654
Come inside,
get under the table.

16:28.654 --> 16:31.032
JAN: It's not an air raid.

16:31.032 --> 16:33.117
Look.

16:33.117 --> 16:34.243
It's not an air raid.
Come on, Miep.

16:34.243 --> 16:35.203
Come.

16:35.203 --> 16:37.747
MIEP: Jan!

16:37.747 --> 16:40.374
JAN: Come on.

16:44.212 --> 16:46.589
MIEP: It's the Allies!

16:48.674 --> 16:49.800
JAN: Beans!

16:49.800 --> 16:51.844
MIEP: Oh my God. Sugar.

16:53.679 --> 16:56.557
JAN: Chocolate!
MIEP: Oh.

17:06.234 --> 17:07.735
Ohh.

17:09.445 --> 17:15.952
(cheering)

17:20.414 --> 17:24.335
(cheering)

17:24.335 --> 17:28.881
MIEP: Yes! Woo!
Oh, over there.

17:28.881 --> 17:30.466
CASMIR: This way.
MIEP: Come on.

17:30.466 --> 17:32.093
Come on. Let's go.

17:32.093 --> 17:33.803
<i>♪ Watch the birdie, we'll take
a camera candid shot ♪</i>

17:33.803 --> 17:36.264
<i>♪ Watch the birdie, come on
and give it all you've got ♪</i>

17:36.264 --> 17:38.933
<i>♪ Watch the birdie, just
look around and pick a spot ♪</i>

17:38.933 --> 17:40.935
<i>♪ And hold it ♪</i>

17:40.935 --> 17:43.562
<i>♪ Watch the birdie, just
strike a funny pose a while ♪</i>

17:43.562 --> 17:46.732
<i>♪ Watch the birdie or you
can beat that pose a mile ♪</i>

17:46.732 --> 17:49.318
<i>♪ Watch the birdie and let
me see your pretty smile ♪</i>

17:49.318 --> 17:50.861
MIEP: Is Hitler really dead?

17:50.861 --> 17:51.904
JAN: Do you think the Germans
would've surrendered if the

17:51.904 --> 17:54.156
bastard wasn't dead?

17:55.157 --> 17:56.701
MIEP: Do you think
he's really dead?

17:56.701 --> 17:57.785
CASMIR: The deadest!

17:57.785 --> 17:59.287
(squealing)

17:59.287 --> 18:00.580
MIEP: Jan!

18:00.955 --> 18:07.461
♪ ♪

18:13.050 --> 18:19.849
♪ ♪

18:20.725 --> 18:22.310
JAN: Hello there.

18:23.394 --> 18:26.397
THERESE: I'm sorry.
We have no food to spare.

18:26.397 --> 18:29.191
JAN: I'm not here for food.

18:30.067 --> 18:32.320
My name is Jan Gies.

18:32.320 --> 18:35.656
Are you Therese van Denberg?

18:35.656 --> 18:37.116
THERESE: I am.

18:37.116 --> 18:40.328
JAN: I work with the students
at Amsterdam University.

18:40.328 --> 18:43.331
They said I could
find Liddy Cohen here.

18:43.331 --> 18:45.499
THERESE: No, I'm sorry.

18:45.499 --> 18:48.628
JAN: You didn't take
in a young Jewish girl?

18:51.797 --> 18:53.549
THERESE: You're
here for Saskia?

18:53.549 --> 18:58.054
JAN: Um, this is the
child I'm looking for.

18:59.847 --> 19:03.184
THERESE: That's Saskia.

19:03.893 --> 19:06.395
JAN: Her grandmother is
returning to Amsterdam.

19:06.395 --> 19:10.441
She'd really, well, um...

19:10.441 --> 19:14.153
I'm here to bring her home.

19:17.281 --> 19:20.159
♪ ♪

19:20.159 --> 19:21.619
VICTOR: Well, too late.

19:21.619 --> 19:23.287
BEP: Mr. Kugler's back!

19:23.287 --> 19:24.955
He hid in a cornfield!

19:24.955 --> 19:27.249
MIEP: Mr. Kugler!
VICTOR: Hello, Miep!

19:27.249 --> 19:28.376
JOHANNES: He escaped!
MIEP: Yeah.

19:28.376 --> 19:29.627
JOHANNES: He's
just telling us!

19:29.627 --> 19:31.087
MIEP: Oh, so please go on.

19:31.087 --> 19:33.631
VICTOR: Uh, so I was
transferred around a lot

19:33.631 --> 19:35.925
after Kleiman deserted me.

19:35.925 --> 19:37.760
JOHANNES: Oh, come on
now, my ulcer got me out.

19:37.760 --> 19:40.680
VICTOR: Well, so I was in a
camp near the German border

19:40.680 --> 19:43.599
and one day, they started
marching us somewhere and

19:43.599 --> 19:46.435
I thought before I know it,
I'll be in Hitler's Germany

19:46.435 --> 19:48.354
and I'll never get out.

19:48.354 --> 19:50.773
Unlike Mr. Kleiman,
I don't have an ulcer.

19:50.773 --> 19:51.774
JOHANNES: Uh, it's...
VICTOR: So.

19:51.774 --> 19:53.651
JOHANNES: A legitimate ulcer.

19:53.943 --> 19:56.779
VICTOR: So I dropped
behind the group and I.

19:56.779 --> 19:58.030
BEP: Hid in a cornfield!

19:58.030 --> 20:00.449
VICTOR: Uh, I'm not
at the cornfield yet.

20:00.449 --> 20:02.618
First, I get bombed.

20:02.618 --> 20:03.911
BEP: Oh, dear.

20:03.911 --> 20:05.955
VICTOR: The guards
start yelling, "Lie down!

20:05.955 --> 20:07.248
Hit the dirt!"

20:07.248 --> 20:08.624
So I did.

20:08.624 --> 20:10.292
(laughing)

20:10.292 --> 20:13.170
And, and, and I was
near a cornfield,

20:13.170 --> 20:15.965
so I did like this and I.

20:15.965 --> 20:18.300
BEP: You rolled
yourself into the cornfield?

20:18.300 --> 20:19.760
VICTOR: Exactly!

20:19.760 --> 20:21.846
And then, when the, when
the planes were gone,

20:21.846 --> 20:24.765
the guards started yelling,
"Everyone get up!"

20:24.765 --> 20:27.435
And I stayed down.

20:27.435 --> 20:28.853
BEP: Uh, you stayed down!

20:28.853 --> 20:32.523
VICTOR: And then
eventually, I, I got up.

20:32.523 --> 20:34.233
BEP: You got up.

20:34.233 --> 20:38.112
VICTOR: And I walked
to the nearest village.

20:38.112 --> 20:42.324
I, I find a bike,
and I rode home.

20:42.324 --> 20:43.784
BEP: Oh, my God.

20:43.784 --> 20:46.328
This is, this is the most
exciting thing I've ever heard!

20:46.328 --> 20:48.247
MIEP: So nice to have some
good news after so many

20:48.247 --> 20:49.707
months of worrying.

20:49.707 --> 20:51.125
BEP: I'm surprised we
don't have ulcers

20:51.125 --> 20:52.501
we worried so much.

20:52.501 --> 20:54.795
JOHANNES: For the record,
it is a legitimate ulcer.

20:54.795 --> 20:57.590
VICTOR: Yeah, well.
MIEP: Okay. We get it.

20:57.590 --> 21:00.176
VICTOR: And, oh, Jan!
MIEP: Look who's back!

21:00.176 --> 21:01.594
BEP: He hid in a cornfield!

21:01.594 --> 21:03.137
JAN: Welcome back.
VICTOR: Thank you.

21:03.137 --> 21:05.473
JAN: Really good to see you.

21:07.433 --> 21:10.978
MIEP: What is it?
What's wrong?

21:12.062 --> 21:15.983
JAN: I, um, uh, I
went to get Liddy.

21:15.983 --> 21:19.987
Um, she got diphtheria six
months ago and the parents

21:19.987 --> 21:22.615
called a doctor to the house.

21:22.615 --> 21:26.202
But he knew, uh, knew that,

21:26.202 --> 21:29.330
that she wasn't theirs
and she was hiding.

21:29.330 --> 21:33.459
And he wouldn't, he wouldn't
treat her because she was,

21:33.459 --> 21:35.127
she was Jewish.

21:35.127 --> 21:37.630
She, she died.

21:39.632 --> 21:42.551
She died.
I'm so sorry.

21:43.969 --> 21:48.098
But I do, I do
have some good news.

21:53.354 --> 21:55.356
MIEP: Jan said that their
train was getting in at 1:00

21:55.356 --> 21:57.525
and that he'd
bring them right over.

21:57.525 --> 21:59.026
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Oh, don't
just stand there,

21:59.026 --> 22:00.236
you're making me nervous.

22:00.236 --> 22:01.612
Have a seat.

22:01.612 --> 22:04.156
MIEP: Oh, sorry.

22:06.534 --> 22:08.494
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Uh, you said
the foster mother is coming.

22:08.494 --> 22:12.665
We should probably get more
chairs and set them around.

22:16.502 --> 22:19.088
Where are the
rest of the chairs?

22:19.088 --> 22:20.464
MIEP: Yeah. Right.

22:20.464 --> 22:23.300
Um, this is the only one left.

22:23.300 --> 22:25.761
We had to use
them for firewood.

22:25.761 --> 22:27.888
Uh, you have to understand
how bad it was here.

22:27.888 --> 22:29.348
There was no food,
there was no fire.

22:29.348 --> 22:30.808
MRS. STOPPELMAN: Do I?
Do I have to understand?

22:30.808 --> 22:33.394
Why is it always me
that has to understand?

22:33.394 --> 22:36.438
They tell me my granddaughter
Liddy is dead, they say,

22:36.438 --> 22:38.524
"You have to understand.
We did the best we could."

22:38.524 --> 22:39.650
MIEP: I know.

22:39.650 --> 22:40.901
MRS. STOPPELMAN:
No, you don't know!

22:40.901 --> 22:43.279
You don't know what it's
like to lose everything!

22:43.279 --> 22:46.907
My daughter, my son-in-law,
my granddaughter,

22:46.907 --> 22:48.576
and I know it's silly because
they're only chairs

22:48.576 --> 22:50.077
but they were my chairs.

22:50.077 --> 22:54.373
Mine. You had no right.

23:01.839 --> 23:03.882
MIEP: Oh, here they come.

23:03.882 --> 23:05.801
MRS. STOPPELMAN: I'm sweating,
I'm so nervous.

23:05.801 --> 23:09.763
MIEP: Oh, what, what about,
what about Kabouter Spillebeen?

23:09.763 --> 23:11.015
Alfred always
really liked this.

23:11.015 --> 23:12.349
It could be a good icebreaker.

23:12.349 --> 23:13.767
MRS. STOPPELMAN:
He's my grandson.

23:13.767 --> 23:15.603
I don't need an icebreaker.

23:15.603 --> 23:17.313
MIEP: No, of course not.

23:17.313 --> 23:19.648
You're right.

23:22.109 --> 23:25.112
JAN: Sorry, the
train was a bit late.

23:25.112 --> 23:27.865
There he is.

23:33.871 --> 23:37.499
MRS. STOPPELMAN:
Hello there, Alfred.

23:37.499 --> 23:41.003
Do you remember me?

23:42.630 --> 23:44.131
VERA: We call him Johann.

23:44.131 --> 23:46.592
But he'll
readjust back to Alfred.

23:46.592 --> 23:48.510
He's very sweet.

23:48.510 --> 23:51.138
Wanna go and say hello?

23:51.138 --> 23:53.682
MRS. STOPPELMAN: I'm your Oma.

23:57.811 --> 24:01.315
Oh. Ooh.

24:01.315 --> 24:06.987
Um, maybe you
remember this little man?

24:06.987 --> 24:10.658
You used to love
to play with him.

24:10.658 --> 24:16.455
In fact, one day you broke
him all to pieces and

24:16.455 --> 24:20.334
we glued him back together.

24:20.334 --> 24:23.045
Do you remember that?

24:23.045 --> 24:25.881
Here, you can hold him.

24:25.881 --> 24:27.966
There we are.

24:27.966 --> 24:29.218
Oh, look, look.

24:29.218 --> 24:32.846
Can you see where we
glued him back together?

24:36.433 --> 24:39.603
ALFRED: I remember you.

24:49.426 --> 24:50.512
♪ ♪

24:55.911 --> 24:57.663
JAN: Alfred's foster mother
is going to stay the night

24:57.663 --> 24:59.790
to help him settle in.

24:59.790 --> 25:05.212
MIEP: Oh, well, let's go out
and give them some privacy.

25:06.213 --> 25:08.298
JAN: Yeah.

25:20.144 --> 25:23.814
MIEP: God.

25:29.361 --> 25:32.281
That's Mrs. van Pels'
handwriting.

25:32.281 --> 25:35.284
See, she underlined cheese.

25:35.284 --> 25:39.413
I can just hear
her saying it, um,

25:39.413 --> 25:43.125
"Don't forget, Miep, don't
forget to find cheese."

25:43.125 --> 25:46.253
God, that woman loved cheese.

25:46.253 --> 25:49.173
Loves.

25:56.180 --> 26:00.392
It's been a month
since liberation.

26:01.226 --> 26:05.522
Every day, I go to work
and I think this will be it.

26:05.522 --> 26:07.983
This will be the day.

26:07.983 --> 26:10.569
And the door opens up
and it's not them.

26:10.569 --> 26:13.363
It's never them.

26:13.739 --> 26:15.991
JAN: It's still early.

26:15.991 --> 26:18.410
The trains are only
just back up and running.

26:18.410 --> 26:21.371
You'll see.

26:21.371 --> 26:24.333
More people are going
to start coming home.

26:25.209 --> 26:30.839
(train whistle)

26:31.298 --> 26:34.092
WOMAN: This way, please.
Stand in line.

26:40.766 --> 26:43.811
JAN: For government benefits,
please step to the right.

26:44.686 --> 26:46.063
WOMAN: My, uh, last name.

26:46.063 --> 26:47.397
SOPHIE: Excuse me?

26:47.397 --> 26:48.941
JAN: Hi, how can I help?

26:48.941 --> 26:51.819
SOPHIE: I was in Auschwitz,
then a DP camp in Krakow.

26:51.819 --> 26:54.238
They said I qualify for
services from the city if

26:54.238 --> 26:55.614
I can show I lived here.

26:55.614 --> 26:57.533
JAN: Okay. Yes.
SOPHIE: I don't have papers.

26:57.533 --> 26:58.951
JAN: That's, that's fine.
That's fine.

26:58.951 --> 27:00.619
Um, are you from Amsterdam?

27:00.619 --> 27:02.329
SOPHIE: Yes.

27:02.329 --> 27:06.792
JAN: And do you have,
um, any contacts here?

27:06.792 --> 27:07.751
SOPHIE: No.

27:07.751 --> 27:10.212
My mother and father are gone.

27:10.212 --> 27:13.924
JAN: I'm so sorry.

27:13.924 --> 27:16.176
If you wait, my colleague
Lena will be able to take

27:16.176 --> 27:19.513
your details, put you
into our system, okay?

27:27.312 --> 27:29.773
Excuse me.

27:29.773 --> 27:34.319
May I ask, in Auschwitz, did
you meet the Frank family?

27:34.319 --> 27:36.488
Otto and Edith Frank?

27:36.488 --> 27:38.991
Maybe their daughters,
Anne and Margot?

27:39.366 --> 27:41.451
SOPHIE: No.
I'm sorry.

27:41.451 --> 27:44.079
JAN: Yeah.
Thank you.

27:46.957 --> 27:52.796
(PA announcements)

27:54.464 --> 27:57.217
JAN: Max?

27:57.217 --> 27:59.386
Max!

28:00.137 --> 28:01.388
Miep!

28:01.388 --> 28:02.931
Miep, come out!

28:02.931 --> 28:05.684
Miep!

28:08.687 --> 28:10.522
Miep!

28:10.522 --> 28:12.357
Come on. Come on. Come on.

28:12.357 --> 28:14.067
MIEP: What's wrong?

28:16.570 --> 28:18.655
JAN: Otto is coming home.

28:18.655 --> 28:21.950
MIEP: What?
JAN: Yes, yes.

28:21.950 --> 28:23.243
I ran into Max at the station.

28:23.243 --> 28:25.162
MIEP: Wait, Max?
JAN: Max, Max Stoppelman.

28:25.162 --> 28:26.830
He's back.

28:26.830 --> 28:29.291
And he said he saw
someone he knew at Auschwitz.

28:29.291 --> 28:30.751
MIEP: Max was in Auschwitz?

28:30.751 --> 28:33.629
JAN: Yes, and he saw someone
who knew Otto and said he

28:33.629 --> 28:35.255
survived and he's coming home.

28:35.255 --> 28:36.298
MIEP: Wait. Who?

28:36.298 --> 28:37.633
Who did Max run into?

28:37.633 --> 28:39.092
JAN: I don't know,
but they knew Otto.

28:39.092 --> 28:40.552
MIEP: Well, we shouldn't
get our hopes up.

28:40.552 --> 28:42.804
We don't know who said it.
It's third-hand information.

28:42.804 --> 28:46.183
JAN: It's real this time.
He's coming home.

28:46.183 --> 28:48.727
He's coming.

28:56.860 --> 29:03.325
♪ ♪

29:16.421 --> 29:19.049
MIEP: Mr. Frank.

29:22.344 --> 29:25.889
OTTO: Hello, Miep. Jan.

29:28.558 --> 29:31.520
MIEP: Come in.
Come in.

29:31.520 --> 29:34.147
Come inside.

29:38.235 --> 29:41.697
He's saying hello to
the warehouse workers.

29:42.114 --> 29:45.158
Don't ask him about anyone.

29:45.158 --> 29:47.995
JOHANNES: Does he know?
Did he tell you?

29:51.999 --> 29:54.835
MIEP: Mrs. Frank is gone.

29:56.336 --> 29:59.131
So is Mr. van Pels.

29:59.548 --> 30:02.300
He lost track of Dr. Pfeffer
and Mrs. van Pels but

30:02.300 --> 30:04.970
they weren't well so
he's not optimistic.

30:04.970 --> 30:08.181
But we have reason to hope
for Peter and the girls.

30:08.181 --> 30:09.891
Peter was with him in
Auschwitz and got marched

30:09.891 --> 30:12.185
away by the Nazis just
before liberation.

30:12.185 --> 30:13.895
And the girls were
in Bergen-Belsen,

30:13.895 --> 30:16.064
which is a work camp,
not a death camp.

30:16.064 --> 30:18.233
So that's really,
really good news.

30:18.233 --> 30:21.611
And they're strong and
we're gonna find them.

30:22.029 --> 30:24.156
The Red Cross posts a list
each day of those who have

30:24.156 --> 30:25.574
come back from the camps.

30:25.574 --> 30:27.868
And I have copies.

30:27.868 --> 30:31.455
Um, here, Bep, go through the
list and find out everyone

30:31.455 --> 30:32.956
who was at Bergen-Belsen.

30:32.956 --> 30:34.499
BEP: Yeah.

30:34.499 --> 30:35.834
MIEP: Divide them up and we'll
write them letters to ask if

30:35.834 --> 30:37.586
any of them know anything
about Anne and Margot.

30:37.586 --> 30:39.087
Jan will keep checking at the
train station and we'll just

30:39.087 --> 30:41.715
keep checking the
Red Cross lists.

30:41.715 --> 30:46.261
OTTO: Miep has gotten
quite bossy in my absence.

30:46.970 --> 30:50.766
JOHANNES: Yes.
She has.

30:52.642 --> 30:54.686
VICTOR: It's good to
have you back, sir.

30:54.686 --> 30:56.897
BEP: Very good.

31:03.153 --> 31:06.740
♪ ♪

31:06.740 --> 31:11.578
OTTO: I am, uh, heartbroken
and I miss my family,

31:11.578 --> 31:14.998
but I'm here.

31:16.500 --> 31:20.504
And that is
because of all of you.

31:25.258 --> 31:32.057
♪ ♪

31:38.151 --> 31:43.527
(bell tolling)

31:43.902 --> 31:45.237
MIEP: I already hate them.

31:45.237 --> 31:47.280
OTTO: Miep, stop. It's fine.
MIEP: No, it's not.

31:47.280 --> 31:48.365
They're living in
your apartment.

31:48.365 --> 31:50.158
It's yours.
You should get it back.

31:50.158 --> 31:52.452
Can't you do something?
The City should do something.

31:52.452 --> 31:54.371
JAN: We're trying to figure
out what to do about

31:54.371 --> 31:55.455
people coming back.

31:55.455 --> 31:56.581
MIEP: I'll tell
you what to do.

31:56.581 --> 31:57.707
Give people back
their old apartments.

31:57.707 --> 32:00.043
OTTO: Shh, shh, shh, shh.

32:00.794 --> 32:02.045
RICHARD: Can we help you?

32:02.045 --> 32:04.589
OTTO: Hello, I'm Otto Frank.

32:04.589 --> 32:05.841
MIEP: You're living
in his apartment.

32:05.841 --> 32:06.967
OTTO: Miep.
JAN: Miep.

32:06.967 --> 32:08.260
ILSE: We moved
here six months ago.

32:08.260 --> 32:09.636
No one told us.

32:09.636 --> 32:10.929
RICHARD: You have to take
it up with the landlord,

32:10.929 --> 32:11.930
I'm afraid.

32:11.930 --> 32:13.473
OTTO: No, no,
you misunderstand.

32:13.473 --> 32:17.018
I'm not here to make you move.
I'm here to make a request.

32:17.018 --> 32:20.188
Um, these are my daughters.

32:20.188 --> 32:23.733
This is Anne and Margot.

32:24.192 --> 32:26.236
When they return to Amsterdam,
they will come here because

32:26.236 --> 32:28.238
this was their home.

32:28.238 --> 32:32.742
Please, tell
them Papa is fine.

32:32.742 --> 32:34.619
He's at Miep's.

32:34.619 --> 32:37.873
MIEP: Here, um, write it
down so you don't forget.

32:37.873 --> 32:40.584
"Papa is fine.
He's at Miep's."

32:42.169 --> 32:48.967
(typewriter clacking)

32:56.349 --> 33:03.231
♪ ♪

33:13.617 --> 33:20.290
♪ ♪

33:23.501 --> 33:25.003
JAN: Thank you.

33:26.630 --> 33:28.131
RED CROSS WORKER: Rose, please.

33:28.131 --> 33:30.717
We have no more information
than what's on these lists.

33:30.717 --> 33:32.385
MIEP: Excuse me, sorry,
which list is this?

33:32.385 --> 33:34.763
RED CROSS WORKER:
Confirmed dead.

33:36.056 --> 33:38.433
MIEP: Sorry.

33:38.892 --> 33:42.312
(sighing)

33:45.523 --> 33:47.484
The girls aren't on here.

33:47.484 --> 33:49.778
They're not on here!

33:59.162 --> 34:02.916
OTTO: Van Pels, Peter,

34:03.583 --> 34:07.212
May 5th, 1945, Mauthausen.

34:11.633 --> 34:18.223
♪ ♪

34:25.855 --> 34:28.400
(sighing)

34:28.400 --> 34:32.279
Hermann van Pels started
as my business partner.

34:32.279 --> 34:36.324
But he quickly
became my friend.

34:36.658 --> 34:39.869
The last time I saw him,
he wasn't well at all.

34:39.869 --> 34:43.415
He was chosen to go
to the left and, uh,

34:43.415 --> 34:46.876
and I to the right.

34:46.876 --> 34:51.131
After he was gone, uh, I
became quite close to Peter.

34:51.131 --> 34:55.093
Uh, he took care of me
like you would a father.

34:56.261 --> 34:59.931
A few days before the
liberation, he came,

34:59.931 --> 35:02.475
they came to get me.

35:02.475 --> 35:05.562
They wanted everyone
who was there to leave.

35:05.562 --> 35:08.106
A forced march.

35:08.106 --> 35:10.191
He was afraid if I
stayed they would kill me.

35:10.191 --> 35:14.571
But I told him I couldn't go
because I was, I was too sick.

35:14.571 --> 35:19.159
And, uh, we said our goodbyes.

35:21.494 --> 35:25.248
He was a good man, Peter.

35:25.957 --> 35:31.880
He was a strong, and
brave, and a loving son.

35:32.589 --> 35:35.842
And I know that
his father would,

35:35.842 --> 35:38.845
would want us to say
Kaddish for him.

35:41.097 --> 35:42.307
(Hebrew prayer)

35:42.307 --> 35:45.268
Yitgadal v'yitkadash
sh'meih raba.

35:45.268 --> 35:49.189
B'al'ma di v'ra chiruteih,
v'yamlich malchuteih,

35:49.189 --> 35:50.982
b'chayeichon uv'yomeichon

35:50.982 --> 35:53.568
uv'chayei d'chol
beit yisra-eil,

35:53.568 --> 35:56.321
baagala uvizman kariv, v'imru.

35:56.321 --> 35:57.781
Amein.

35:57.781 --> 36:04.579
(prayer continues)

36:04.579 --> 36:11.044
♪ ♪

36:18.635 --> 36:25.392
♪ ♪

36:27.811 --> 36:29.688
MIEP: What are you thinking?

36:29.688 --> 36:32.690
JAN: Just thinking
about you, actually.

36:32.690 --> 36:35.235
MIEP: What about me?

36:35.235 --> 36:37.696
JAN: I was thinking that I
don't know your favorite color.

36:37.696 --> 36:39.364
MIEP: Red.

36:39.364 --> 36:40.907
JAN: So I'd have
guessed yellow.

36:40.907 --> 36:42.450
MIEP: Yellow?
JAN: Yeah.

36:42.450 --> 36:44.160
MIEP: Are you insane?

36:44.160 --> 36:46.204
JAN: It's funny
though, isn't it?

36:46.204 --> 36:48.081
Being with someone
for so long,

36:48.081 --> 36:50.208
you know their heart,
their soul,

36:50.208 --> 36:52.836
you know what they're thinking
before they think it,

36:52.836 --> 36:55.463
but you don't
know their favorite color.

36:55.463 --> 36:59.259
MIEP: What am I thinking?

36:59.884 --> 37:02.095
JAN: That you don't want to
go home just yet because

37:02.095 --> 37:06.433
Mr. Frank is there, and
you hate to see him sad,

37:06.433 --> 37:08.435
and that's what he is,

37:08.435 --> 37:12.188
so you'd like to do another
loop around the park.

37:15.984 --> 37:17.902
MIEP: What's your
favorite color?

37:17.902 --> 37:20.613
JAN: Come on.
You know.

37:20.613 --> 37:21.740
Obvious.

37:21.740 --> 37:23.700
MIEP: Is it?
JAN: Yes!

37:23.700 --> 37:26.870
I scream this color.
I shout it from the rooftops.

37:26.870 --> 37:28.496
This color is my heritage!

37:28.496 --> 37:30.415
MIEP: Oh. Orange.

37:30.415 --> 37:33.168
JAN: Yes!
I'm a Dutchman!

37:33.168 --> 37:36.421
(laughing)

37:36.421 --> 37:39.299
MIEP: And, and you're
a little bit ginger.

37:39.299 --> 37:41.801
JAN: Oh! Yes!

37:41.801 --> 37:44.220
That's how seriously
I take this color!

37:44.554 --> 37:46.848
ISAAC: Excuse me.
Excuse me.

37:47.682 --> 37:49.851
Yes, it's, it's, it's you.

37:49.851 --> 37:51.853
You, um, you helped us.

37:51.853 --> 37:53.313
JAN: Uh, sorry, I...

37:53.313 --> 37:55.607
ISAAC: In, in the church, you,
you brought us a picture

37:55.607 --> 37:56.858
of our boy, Nathan.

37:56.858 --> 38:00.028
That's, that's him, there.
That's Nathan.

38:00.028 --> 38:02.447
We were reunited
about a month ago.

38:02.447 --> 38:04.407
It's been, it's been great.

38:04.407 --> 38:06.743
MAYA: We are so grateful.

38:06.743 --> 38:10.455
Sorry to bother you,
but he saved our family.

38:10.455 --> 38:13.541
MIEP: No, no, that's fine.
It's great.

38:13.541 --> 38:15.502
ISAAC: Well, thank you.

38:15.502 --> 38:19.672
Thank you for everything.

38:19.672 --> 38:20.632
JAN: Lovely to see you again.

38:20.632 --> 38:22.884
MAYA: Thank you.

38:22.884 --> 38:25.011
JAN: Bye, Nathan.
NATHAN: Bye-bye.

38:34.187 --> 38:37.190
JAN: Another loop?
MIEP: Uh-hmm.

38:41.361 --> 38:42.654
Morning!

38:42.654 --> 38:44.113
BEP: Look what I found.

38:44.113 --> 38:46.074
Real coffee.

38:46.074 --> 38:47.909
OTTO: Oh, Bep.

38:47.909 --> 38:49.327
BEP: I bought it with the
money I was supposed to use

38:49.327 --> 38:50.912
to buy typewriter ink.

38:50.912 --> 38:52.789
MIEP: Bep, how am I supposed
to write the invoices?

38:52.789 --> 38:55.291
OTTO: This is
extraordinary, smell.

38:55.625 --> 38:57.669
MIEP: Oh, okay.
I'll handwrite the invoices.

38:57.669 --> 38:59.838
OTTO: No, go ahead.
I'll make the coffee.

38:59.838 --> 39:01.464
I don't like the way you make
it, it's too much milk,

39:01.464 --> 39:03.216
it's always cold.

39:03.216 --> 39:04.467
MIEP: All these years,
now you tell me?

39:04.467 --> 39:07.220
OTTO: Yeah.
Temperature's important, Miep.

39:10.598 --> 39:11.975
BEP: I put the
mail on your desk.

39:11.975 --> 39:13.351
MIEP: Anything
from the Red Cross?

39:13.351 --> 39:15.937
BEP: No, I don't think so.

39:16.896 --> 39:18.231
MIEP: Can I help you?

39:18.231 --> 39:20.316
JANNI: I'm looking
for Otto Frank.

39:20.316 --> 39:22.068
MIEP: Is he expecting you?

39:22.068 --> 39:23.987
JANNI: No.

39:23.987 --> 39:26.864
Um, I knew his daughters.

39:26.864 --> 39:29.075
At Bergen-Belsen.

39:29.075 --> 39:34.872
I, I received this letter,
uh, asking for information.

39:36.249 --> 39:39.669
I have information.

39:42.088 --> 39:44.215
MIEP: Are they...

39:44.215 --> 39:47.975
OTTO: It's brewing now.
Five more.

39:47.975 --> 39:49.879
♪ ♪

39:55.894 --> 40:02.150
(crying)

40:03.902 --> 40:06.613
JOHANNES: You were a
good friend to them.

40:06.613 --> 40:09.115
You made their lives better.

40:09.115 --> 40:11.034
VICTOR: We all did.

40:11.034 --> 40:12.702
And they knew.

40:12.702 --> 40:15.663
We can take comfort in that.

40:17.332 --> 40:19.334
For the two years
that they were here,

40:19.334 --> 40:22.128
they knew that people
cared for them.

40:22.128 --> 40:25.340
They knew they mattered.

40:28.384 --> 40:30.470
MIEP: The first time Anne
came into the office,

40:30.470 --> 40:32.639
she was just five years old.

40:32.639 --> 40:35.975
She sat down at my desk

40:35.975 --> 40:38.061
and started playing
with my typewriter.

40:38.061 --> 40:39.145
VICTOR: I remember.

40:39.145 --> 40:41.105
She was wearing a
fuzzy white coat.

40:41.105 --> 40:43.483
I was worried she was
going to get ink on it.

40:43.483 --> 40:44.942
BEP: Uh-hmm.

40:44.942 --> 40:46.194
VICTOR: I thought her mother
should say something, but.

40:46.194 --> 40:48.404
BEP: Oh, you couldn't
say anything to Anne.

40:48.404 --> 40:50.365
She was always so...

40:50.365 --> 40:53.785
MIEP: Anne.
BEP: That's right.

40:53.785 --> 40:56.996
She was always so Anne.

40:56.996 --> 41:00.291
And Margot was
always just so Margot.

41:01.876 --> 41:04.504
MIEP: Margot followed her
mother around like a shadow.

41:04.504 --> 41:06.673
She was so polite,

41:06.673 --> 41:09.425
and she drank the hot milk I
gave her and said "thank you"

41:09.425 --> 41:13.137
in this sweet little voice,

41:13.137 --> 41:15.515
while Anne was just clattering
away at the typewriter like

41:15.515 --> 41:18.601
she had to get all her
thoughts down all at once.

41:20.728 --> 41:23.856
Her diary.

41:29.821 --> 41:36.619
♪ ♪

41:51.134 --> 41:57.390
♪ ♪

42:06.024 --> 42:07.442
Mr. Frank.

42:07.442 --> 42:10.153
OTTO: Not now, Miep.

42:10.778 --> 42:12.030
MIEP: I'd just really like to...

42:12.030 --> 42:15.908
OTTO: Please. Not now.

42:25.334 --> 42:28.254
MIEP: I was saving this.

42:28.254 --> 42:31.424
For her.

42:31.424 --> 42:34.594
You should have it.

42:47.732 --> 42:53.946
♪ ♪

42:58.826 --> 43:05.374
♪ ♪

43:11.339 --> 43:18.096
♪ ♪

43:24.352 --> 43:31.067
♪ ♪

43:36.572 --> 43:43.371
♪ ♪

43:43.830 --> 43:47.959
(train whistle)

43:52.505 --> 43:59.303
♪ ♪

44:06.727 --> 44:11.357
(train bell ringing)

44:11.357 --> 44:18.156
♪ ♪

44:24.120 --> 44:29.083
♪ ♪

44:29.083 --> 44:31.961
They're not coming back.

44:31.961 --> 44:33.713
Everyone's gone.

44:33.713 --> 44:38.759
(crying)

44:44.682 --> 44:49.770
♪ ♪

44:49.770 --> 44:53.399
I thought I was
saved for a reason.

44:54.192 --> 44:58.446
I thought maybe
that's why I didn't die.

44:58.446 --> 45:02.783
And why my mother sent me
away to be here in Amsterdam.

45:04.535 --> 45:08.331
I thought maybe I'm
supposed to be here

45:08.331 --> 45:11.000
so that the girls would live.

45:11.000 --> 45:12.335
JAN: Miep.
MIEP: See?

45:12.335 --> 45:16.589
You don't know what I'm
thinking all the time.

45:16.839 --> 45:19.634
You don't know that I've been
thinking that they have to

45:19.634 --> 45:23.262
come back because then
it would make sense of

45:23.262 --> 45:26.057
my existence.

45:30.645 --> 45:34.065
It would make
sense in my head.

45:37.276 --> 45:41.238
JAN: We don't know the reason
why one person is spared and

45:41.238 --> 45:43.532
the other isn't.

45:43.532 --> 45:49.121
All we can do is make
a choice every day

45:49.121 --> 45:52.208
to do something good.

45:52.208 --> 45:54.710
And you made that choice.

45:54.710 --> 45:57.838
Every day.

45:57.838 --> 46:01.550
That's all we
have control over.

46:01.550 --> 46:05.012
Apples and carrots.

46:05.012 --> 46:07.848
Cheese.

46:07.848 --> 46:11.686
And walking
upstairs when it was hard.

46:19.110 --> 46:21.445
MIEP: It's after work.
Where is he?

46:21.445 --> 46:23.072
JAN: He's probably
still at the office.

46:23.072 --> 46:24.907
MIEP: Oh, what if he's thrown
himself into the canal or

46:24.907 --> 46:26.450
in front of a tram?

46:26.450 --> 46:29.662
Or just wandering around alone
because he has no one left,

46:29.662 --> 46:31.288
they've all gone.

46:31.288 --> 46:32.832
Oh, God, I shouldn't have
given him the diary,

46:32.832 --> 46:34.208
I should've waited.

46:34.208 --> 46:38.129
JAN: No, you should have.
You did the right thing.

46:38.129 --> 46:39.630
It was kind.

46:39.630 --> 46:41.507
And he knows that.

46:41.507 --> 46:43.884
(door opens)

46:44.385 --> 46:46.595
MIEP: Mr. Frank?

47:06.824 --> 47:10.036
(sighing)

47:11.495 --> 47:13.998
OTTO: Did you read this?

47:15.458 --> 47:18.461
I had no idea.

47:20.755 --> 47:23.924
The things she writes about.

47:25.301 --> 47:27.803
The way she writes,
the way she thinks.

47:29.013 --> 47:33.601
I knew she was a quick and
clever girl, but she was...

47:39.190 --> 47:42.401
I feel like I didn't know her.

47:46.030 --> 47:50.368
We were hiding as a family
but she was hiding, too.

47:51.243 --> 47:54.538
She was hiding a part of
herself that maybe

47:54.538 --> 47:57.458
she didn't want me to see.

47:58.626 --> 48:01.712
But I'm so glad I did.

48:02.880 --> 48:06.175
Thank you, Miep.

48:09.220 --> 48:14.642
It was like getting
to watch her grow up.

48:23.234 --> 48:26.153
You saved this.

48:28.322 --> 48:30.866
You gave it to me.

48:31.575 --> 48:35.329
Thank you.

48:40.376 --> 48:45.172
(crying)

48:47.550 --> 48:50.094
Thank you.

49:05.734 --> 49:08.779
JAN: I want you
to stay with us.

49:08.779 --> 49:11.907
We're moving into a new place.

49:11.907 --> 49:14.535
We want you to
live there with us.

49:14.535 --> 49:16.704
MIEP: Yeah.
You have to.

49:16.704 --> 49:20.541
And we can talk about them as
much or as little as you like,

49:20.541 --> 49:23.043
but we can.

49:24.003 --> 49:26.797
Please, Mr. Frank.

49:28.591 --> 49:31.719
OTTO: Well, thank you.

49:31.719 --> 49:33.888
But first, you
must call me Otto.

49:33.888 --> 49:35.556
(laughing)

49:36.807 --> 49:39.059
Thank you.

49:44.607 --> 49:46.734
What are the vegetables?

49:46.734 --> 49:48.319
MIEP: Um, parsnips.

